Client :
	- Nickname of a client is 9 characters max (used to distinguish from other clients).

Server:
	- All servers must have the following information about all clients:
		- the real name of the host that the client is running on
		- the username of the client on that host
		- and the server to which the client is connected.

Channels :
	- named group in which clients will all receive messages addressed to that channel.
	- name is 200 characters max.
	- first character has to be '&' or '#'.
	- name cannot contain a space (' '), a control G (^G or ASCII 7), or a comma (',').
	
User :
	- A user may join several channels at once. A limit of 10 is RECOMMENDED.



MODE :
	- When a user join a channel:
		- if the channel doesn't exist, the channel is created and the user becomes a channel operator.
		- if the channel exists, whether the user joins is entirely decided by the current modes of the channel. For example if the channel is invite-only (+i), the user may only join if the user is invited.
		
		
file_descriptor : int

struct :
	- addrinfo :
		struct addrinfo {
    			int              ai_flags;     // AI_PASSIVE, AI_CANONNAME, etc.
    			int              ai_family;    // AF_INET, AF_INET6, AF_UNSPEC
    			int              ai_socktype;  // SOCK_STREAM, SOCK_DGRAM
    			int              ai_protocol;  // use 0 for "any"
    			size_t           ai_addrlen;   // size of ai_addr in bytes
    			struct sockaddr *ai_addr;      // struct sockaddr_in or _in6 (we usually use this)
    			char            *ai_canonname; // full canonical hostname

    			struct addrinfo *ai_next;      // linked list, next node
		};
		
	- sockaddr :
		struct sockaddr {
    			unsigned short    sa_family;    // address family, AF_xxx
    			char              sa_data[14];  // 14 bytes of protocol address
		}; 
		(A call to getaddrinfo() to fill out your struct addrinfo for you is all you’ll need. No need to write it by hand.)
	
	- sockaddr_in : ("in" is for internet)
		struct sockaddr_in {
    			short            sin_family;   // e.g. AF_INET
    			unsigned short   sin_port;     // e.g. htons(3490)
    			struct in_addr   sin_addr;     // see struct in_addr, below
    			char             sin_zero[8];  // (included to pad the structure to the length of a struct sockaddr)
		};

	- in_addr :
		struct in_addr {
    			unsigned long s_addr;  // load with inet_aton()
		};
		
		You usually work on the struct sockaddr_in and then cast it at the last minute to a sockaddr struct to use connect() or bind()
		
IP Adresses : (not needed here since the server and client are on the same machine but cool to know nonetheless)

	To convert Ips (IPv4) into struct in_addr you want to use inet_pton (Presentation TO Network)
	inet_pton(AF_INET, "10.12.110.57", &(sa.sin_addr));

	The old way was to use inet_addr() or inet_aton() but they are now obselete and dont work with IPv6.

	Here is a working version for IPv4 :
	
		char ip4[INET_ADDRSTRLEN];  // space to hold the IPv4 string
		struct sockaddr_in sa;      // pretend this is loaded with something

		inet_ntop(AF_INET, &(sa.sin_addr), ip4, INET_ADDRSTRLEN);

		printf("The IPv4 address is: %s\n", ip4);
		
	You would use inet_ntoa() instead of the macros in the past.
	Note : This code doesn't work with DNS lookup like "www.example.com"
	For that you would need getaddrinfo().
	
	If you want to setup a server to listen to your server IP, prot 3490 (It doesn't listen, it only sets up the structure) :
		
		int status;
		struct addrinfo hints;
		struct addrinfo *servinfo;  // will point to the results

		memset(&hints, 0, sizeof hints); // make sure the struct is empty
		hints.ai_family = AF_UNSPEC;     // don't care IPv4 or IPv6
		hints.ai_socktype = SOCK_STREAM; // TCP stream sockets
		hints.ai_flags = AI_PASSIVE;     // fill in my IP for me

		if ((status = getaddrinfo(NULL, "3490", &hints, &servinfo)) != 0) {
 		   fprintf(stderr, "gai error: %s\n", gai_strerror(status)); // Note : cannot be used in ft_irc, but good for an early version check
 		   exit(1);
		}

		// servinfo now points to a linked list of 1 or more
		// struct addrinfos

		// ... do everything until you don't need servinfo anymore ....

		freeaddrinfo(servinfo); // free the linked-list
		
Socket :
		#include <sys/types.h>
		#include <sys/socket.h>

		int socket(int domain, int type, int protocol); 
	
	
	You basically use the result of getaddrinfo() to feed the socket() function.
	like this :
	
	s = socket(res->ai_family, res->ai_socktype, res->ai_protocol);
	//ai_family is AF_INET, AF_INET6, AF_UNSPEC
	//ai_socktype is SOCK_STREAM, SOCK_DGRAM
	//ai_protocol : use 0 for any (or IPPROTO_TCP for TCP, IPPROTO_UDP for UDP, etc...)
	
	It returns a socket descriptor that is usable for later system calls.
	
	Now that you have a socket that is ready you need to bind it to a local port of your machine (Only useful for the server, as the client will only do a connect()) :	
	
		#include <sys/types.h>
		#include <sys/socket.h>

		int bind(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *my_addr, int addrlen);
		
	Example :
	
		struct addrinfo hints, *res;
		int sockfd;

		// first, load up address structs with getaddrinfo():

		memset(&hints, 0, sizeof hints);
		hints.ai_family = AF_UNSPEC;  // use IPv4 or IPv6, whichever
		hints.ai_socktype = SOCK_STREAM;
		hints.ai_flags = AI_PASSIVE;     // auto fill the host's IP.

		getaddrinfo(NULL, "3490", &hints, &res); // No DNS, listen on 3490

		// make a socket:

		sockfd = socket(res->ai_family, res->ai_socktype, res->ai_protocol);

		// bind it to the port we passed in to getaddrinfo():

		bind(sockfd, res->ai_addr, res->ai_addrlen);
		
	Then to not have the socket hog the port (causing bind() to fail) we need to set this :
	
		int yes=1;
		setsockopt(listener, SOL_SOCKET, SO_REUSEADDR, &yes, sizeof yes);
		
	Now that we used bind() to say "I want to connect there" we have to actually connect() to it (or start listen()ing for a server, then accept() the connections). (used mostly for clients) :
	
		#include <sys/types.h>
		#include <sys/socket.h>

		int connect(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *serv_addr, int addrlen);
		
	Note that you are a client you do not need to bind() as you don't care what port you are using, ther kernel gives you one and, when send() to a server, the server will get the information needed to send() back.
	
	Now for the server we need to listen() for any client connect()ing :
	
		int listen(int sockfd, int backlog); // sockfd is the result form socket(), backlog is the number of connections allowed on the queue.
	
	If we receive a connection we need to use :
	
		#include <sys/types.h>
		#include <sys/socket.h>

		int accept(int sockfd, struct sockaddr *addr, socklen_t *addrlen); 
		
	While the socket is still listening for new connections, a new socket is created and given as output, so now on this new socket, we can now send() and recv().
	addr will be a local sockaddr to use as storage.
	Example (server) :
	
		#include <string.h>
		#include <sys/types.h>
		#include <sys/socket.h>
		#include <netdb.h>

		#define MYPORT "3490"  // the port users will be connecting to
		#define BACKLOG 10     // how many pending connections queue holds

		int main(void)
		{
	  	  struct sockaddr_storage their_addr;
	  	  socklen_t addr_size;
	  	  struct addrinfo hints, *res;
	  	  int sockfd, new_fd;

	  	  // !! don't forget your error checking for these calls !!

	  	  // first, load up address structs with getaddrinfo():

	  	  memset(&hints, 0, sizeof hints);
	  	  hints.ai_family = AF_UNSPEC;  // use IPv4 or IPv6, whichever
	  	  hints.ai_socktype = SOCK_STREAM;
	  	  hints.ai_flags = AI_PASSIVE;     // auto fill the host's IP.

	  	  getaddrinfo(NULL, MYPORT, &hints, &res);

	  	  // make a socket, bind it, and listen on it:

	  	  sockfd = socket(res->ai_family, res->ai_socktype, res->ai_protocol);
	  	  bind(sockfd, res->ai_addr, res->ai_addrlen);
	  	  listen(sockfd, BACKLOG);

	  	  // now accept an incoming connection:

	  	  addr_size = sizeof their_addr;
	  	  new_fd = accept(sockfd, (struct sockaddr *)&their_addr, &addr_size);
			
	What if you want to send() something? :
	
		int send(int sockfd, const void *msg, int len, int flags);
		
	sockfd is where you want to send the message, len is the length of msg, and flags should probably be 0.
	Note that send might not send everything at once. Check that with the output of send(). If that's the case, send() again the rest.
		
	In the sane way if you want to recv() :
	
		int recv(int sockfd, void *buf, int len, int flags);		
	
	sockfd is what you read from, len the length of buf, and flags 0. It returns the number of bytes read. 0 means connection closed.
	
	When everything is finished, just close() the socket descriptor. (On Windows use closesocket() instead of close())
	You could also use shutdown() for more control, but in this case, it is irrelevant.	
	
Blocking :
	
	For ft_irc we cannot use accept as it is blocking, which means that while it is waiting for information it cannot do anything else.
	Instead of accept() we can setup the fd as nonblocking just after setting it up :
		
		sockfd = socket(PF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
		fcntl(sockfd, F_SETFL, O_NONBLOCK);
	
	However doing it this way would consume a lot more CPU resources than normal as your program would stay in a busy-wait state looking for data.
	
	So, instead, we can use poll() to check if there is info ready to read on the fd.
	
	poll :
		
		#include <poll.h>

		int poll(struct pollfd fds[], nfds_t nfds, int timeout);
		
	pollfd has the following structure :
	
		struct pollfd {
			int   fd;         /* file descriptor */
			short events;     /* requested events */
			short revents;    /* returned events */
		};
